I found an colourised etching by Curt Mücke (1885-1940)&hellip;
Print Curt Mücke was a painter and graphic artist from Sondershausen. His motifs often show night scenes, often in winter, like this one. He was a master student of Max Klinger.
The picture shows the Siedelhof in the Schloßgasse in Jena, the building housed a branch of the Jena City Museum from 1927 and was destroyed in the Second World War.

I found a woodcut by Elsa Haensgen-Dingkuhn (1898-1991)&hellip;
PrintSignature Elsa Haensgen-Dingkuhn was a graphic artist and painter from Hamburg. The depiction of children became one of her central themes from the mid-1920s onwards with the birth of her own children. Her descendants run their own website with a selection of her works.
In the &ldquo;Handbuch des Kunstmarktes: Kunstadressbuch für das Deutsche Reich, Danzig und Deutsch-Österreich&rdquo;, published in 1926 by Antiqua Verlags-Gesellschaft Kalkoff, Berlin, she is mentioned on the same page (195) as Wilma Bräuner.
The signature is a good opportunity to point out the dangers of paper silverfish, which have presumably nibbled away parts of the signature here&hellip;

I have acquired a linocut by Elsa Hoppe (1901-1992)&hellip;
PrintSignature Elsa Hoppe was an artist from Göttingen, after whom a street in Göttingen is named. Further information about her can be found in the Göttinger Künstlerlexikon (German) by Thomas Appel. Similar motifs are illustrated in the booklet ‘Elsa Hoppe Grüsse zum Jahreswechsel’ by Karlheinz Stalder, published in 1999 by Goltze, Göttingen, ISBN 3884528572.
Even if the signature is difficult to read, an enquiry with Simone Hübner of the Städtisches Museum Göttingen confirmed that it&rsquo;s a print by Elsa Hoppe&hellip;

I have found a woodcut by Otto Richard Bossert (1874-1919)&hellip;
PrintSignature Otto Richard Bossert was mainly a graphic artist and illustrator who worked in Leipzig. The SLUB Dresden has the catalogue raisonné digitised
The name of the motif is &ldquo;Girl looking up from reading&rdquo;, it is the design for a postcard from 1914.

I have found a woodcut by Paul-Kurt Bartzsch (1917-1994)&hellip;
PrintSignature Paul Kurt Bartzsch was mainly a painter and graphic artist who was born in Dresden and worked in Wolfsburg.
The name of the motif is ‘Škrlatica’, a mountain in the Julian Alps, it is monogrammed in the plate with ‘PKB’ and dated 1954.

Today (26 March) is the opening of the exhibition ‘Was zum Quant?!’ in the Forum Wissen. You can also see a digital exhibit in which I was involved&hellip;
The installation &ldquo;Quantum cosmos Göttingen&rdquo; shows the places where quantum physicists lived and worked in Göttingen from the summer semester of 1921 to the winter semester of 1936/36. The underlying city map is freely scalable, and the timeline at the bottom allows you to select the semester. Comparable to Europeana.4D, GeoTemCo, or the Dariah GeoBrowser&hellip;
The data was collected by Pia Denkmann, the geodata enrichment, JSON transformation and the web frontend are by me. The texts were written by Christine Nawa and Ramona Dölling. The integration into the exhibition was carried out by the agency Cognitio.
